@node "intro"
@{b}Introduction@{ub}

This is a simple telnet client which I made when I needed one and
none of the ones I found worked the way I wanted them to.

The initial version only supported starting from a shell since this was what
I wanted, but the client now has support for running from the Workbench also.

The code is a bit of a hack, but if anyone wants to do anything with it you
are welcome.

	-Peter Bengtsson <tesla@och.nu>
	 27/7-2005

@endnode

@node "cli"
When starting the program from the shell, the first argument must be the host to
connect to and the second is the port number. If the port number is omitted, it
defaults to 23.
@endnode

@node "wb"
Since version 0.6 the client can be started from the Workbench using an icon. Either as a tool
icon or a project icon referring to the telnet binary as the default tool.

The tooltypes supported are the following:

@{b}WINDOW@{ub}
	Specifies the file to open for i/o. This should be a console file specified as e.g.:
	"CON:0/0/640/512/Telnet". Defaults to "CON:0/384/1024/384/Telnet/CLOSE".

@{b}HOST@{ub}
	The host to connect to. Defaults to "127.0.0.1"

@{b}PORT@{ub}
	The port to connect to. Defaults to "23".

@endnode

@node "config"

The configuration file, s:telnet-config, contains a number of lines specifying
the behaviour of the telnet client. The following options exist:

@{b}pen=x@{ub}
	Sets the pen colour (using ansi codes). Specifying -1 will turn the feature off.
	(The same effect as not specifying it)

@{b}paper=x@{ub}
	Sets the paper (background) colour (using ansi codes). Specifying -1 will turn
	the feature off. (The same effect as not specifying it)

@{b}echo=<any|local>@{ub}
	Enables remote echoing if set to any. This is the recommended setting.
	Remote echoing will only be enabled if the server requests it.

@{b}term=x@{ub}
	Sets the terminal name to the specified string. Usually this would be something
	like "amiga" or "amiga-8bit".

@{b}title=<yes|no>@{ub}
	Enables/disables the changing of the title to the host connected to.

@endnode

@node "console"
The telnet command console, accessed by pressing Ctrl+] currently only
has 3 commands.

@{b}help@{ub}
	Prints a list of available commands.

@{b}quit@{ub}
	Abort the telnet session and exit the program.

@{b}resume@{ub}
	Resume the telnet session.

@endnode

